Chief Complaint
6 month follow up
discuss increasing anxiety medication and referral for counceling
History of Present Illness
Patient consented to the use of Freed to record and transcribe notes during this visit.
Vickie Berry, a 72-year-old female, presents for a six-month follow-up, primarily concerned about worsening anxiety. She reports feeling "miserable" and states she's "going nuts" due to her anxiety symptoms.
The patient describes that while her current medication helps with some symptoms, she continues to struggle with the "mental stuff." In an effort to address these ongoing issues, she has decided to seek counseling. She expresses a preference for a female therapist and mentions hearing positive things about Integrity in Kokomo.
Ms. Berry reports that her blood pressure was "really good today," suggesting an improvement in her cardiovascular health. She also notes changes in her foot size, stating that she used to wear size eight-and-a-half shoes but now wears seven-and-a-half. She questions the cause of this change, wondering if it's possible for feet to shrink or if shoe sizes are changing.
The patient acknowledges weight gain and expresses an intention to start walking for exercise. However, she reports getting out of breath easily, which concerns her children who advise her to slow down. This shortness of breath is impacting her ability to increase her physical activity.
Overall, Ms. Berry appears to be struggling with anxiety management despite medication, experiencing changes in her physical health including weight gain and shortness of breath, and is actively seeking additional mental health support through counseling.
